article.description:
Courtney Alexander scored 11 of his 23 points
in the fourth quarter as the New Orleans Hornets preserved their
perfect home record with 102-98 comeback victory over the Minnesota
Timberwolves on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Alexander scores 11 of 23 points in fourth quarter
article.linkText: Alexander, Hornets keep T-Wolves winless on road
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Courtney Alexander showed why the Hornets traded a first-round draft pick to get him.
Alexander

Alexander scored 11 of his 23 points in the fourth quarter as the New Orleans Hornets preserved their perfect home record with 102-98 comeback victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday night. Alexander, who played sparingly but showed scoring potential in his first two NBA seasons with Washington, failed to beat out David Wesley for the starting shooting guard job in training camp. Alexander said defining his role off the bench "was tough at first, but we're getting in that rhythm. It was definitely a good game to get under my belt.'' He hit all 10 of his free throws, eight of them in the final period. He also made a 3-pointer from the corner to tie the game at 94 with just over two minutes left. Alexander "is an exceptional scorer, and I'm very confident that he'll either drive to the hole, get fouled -- he's just got to be aggressive,'' said Jamal Mashburn, who led the Hornets with 25 points and 10 rebounds. "It's a difficult situation when you've been traded, trying to get a feel for a new system ... I just tell him, 'just relax, do what you do best, there's a reason why we got you.'' Baron Davis scored 15, and P.J. Brown had 11 points and nine rebounds for New Orleans, now 5-0 in its new home. Kevin Garnett and reserve Rod Strickland led Minnesota with 16 points each. Troy Hudson added 14, Wally Szczerbiak 13 and Radoslav Nesterovic had 12 points with 12 rebounds. Minnesota, which has lost all four of its road games, led 91-80, the largest lead for either team, early in the fourth quarter. "This was our best game on the road. We just got into a situation where we couldn't make plays. We couldn't make shots,'' Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "They turned up the heat. They made plays and we didn't.'' After Strickland's basket made it 93-84 with about 6:30 left, New Orleans went on a 14-1 run during which Alexander scored seven. "There's no excuse for that,'' Szczerbiak said. "All I can say is we've just got to stop it right now. These meltdowns in the fourth quarter have got to stop.'' Hornets coach Paul Silas couldn't specify what turned the game around so suddenly, other than sheer will. "We were just searching for a combination that would work. We tried everything,'' Silas said. "We reached back and found it from somewhere. Courtney came through for us.'' New Orleans' defense, so strong during the last half of the fourth quarter, was soft in the third period as Minnesota pulled ahead 81-73. Szczerbiak scored eight of Minnesota's first 15 points of the quarter. Szczerbiak was a surprise starter after sitting out the past three games with a sprained left knee. His third-quarter spurt came after a rough first half in which he committed two early fouls and scored four points in 12 minutes. Both teams shot above 50 percent in a first half that saw each score in surges. A fast-break basket by Wesley capped a 12-0 Hornets run for a 14-8 lead. Mashburn, guarded by Garnett, scored 11 in the first quarter and had 17, including two 3-pointers, in the first half. "I almost prefer a bigger guy on me,'' Mashburn said. "Sometimes with smaller guys you can't really feel them and I'm more of a feel player. His length is tremendous but it doesn't bother me.'' Minnesota surged to a 54-53 halftime lead by taking advantage of sloppy play by the Hornets, who committed three turnovers in five possessions late in the half. The Wolves had 14 points off of seven turnovers through the first two periods. Game notes
Hornets reserve forward George Lynch hit his first 3-point attempt of the season in the third quarter. He hit another in the fourth. ... The Timberwolves are now below .500 for the first time since November of 2000, when Minnesota started 2-4 before winning five straight. ... The game had to be stopped briefly in the first half when a mini, remote-controlled blimp used for advertising went out of control and slowly sank onto the court. ... Hornets center Elden Campbell, sidelined with knee soreness that required arthroscopic surgery, felt a small increase in pain Tuesday and did not work out as scheduled Wednesday. "He was supposed to start running today but he was under the weather a little,'' coach Paul Silas said. "It's beginning to get frustrating because we need him.'' Silas could not project when Campbell would return.
